<p>Â Â Â Â Â Â Recently, while browsing at a local Barnes and Noble, I noticed an interesting title on the shelf in the military history section: <em>World War II at Sea: A Global History</em> (Oxford University Press), by Craig L. Symonds. At first, I dismissed it as just another broad, general coverage of the naval aspect of WWIIâ€”only later did I come to a strange realization: until this workâ€™s publication in 2018, there had not been (at least to my knowledge) a single, concise, one-volume coverage of the Second World War at sea (Samuel Eliot Morisonâ€™s <em>The Two Ocean War: A Short History of the United States Navy in the Second World War</em> did come to mind, but the workâ€™s focus is on the U.S. forces). A cursory google search revealed that the book has been very well received, and I couldnâ€™t think of anyone more qualified or better suited than Symonds, â€œthe Ernest J. King Distinguished Professor of Maritime History at the Naval War College and Professor Emeritus at the U.S Naval Academy, where he taught for thirty years and served as a department chair,â€ [^1] to give the incredible story of naval conflict in WWII the treatment it deserves, to give the reader both a panoramic perspective of a global naval war of truly unprecedented scale as well as insight into its human aspects and cost. So, I returned to the bookstore and picked up a copy.</p>

<p>Â Â Â Â Â Â Several pages into the prologue of my copy, Symonds makes an odd claim. In describing the general characteristics of capital ship design in the immediate aftermath of the First World War and Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, he states that â€œThe largest warship in the Royal Navy in 1930 was the battlecruiser HMS <em>Hood</em>, which at 860 feet was the pride of the fleet. While her eight 15-inch guns were the largest then afloat, her Achillesâ€™ heel was her relatively thin armor, which made her more vulnerable than any battleship.â€ The idea that <em>Hood</em>â€™s 15-inch guns were â€œthe largest then afloatâ€ is, quite simply, absurd: the 41cm/45 (16.1 inch) and 16â€/45 naval rifles found on the respective <em>Nagato</em> and <em>Colorado</em> class battleships (with the lead ships commissioned in 1921 and 1923 respectively, years before 1930) were both longer and larger. Even more egregiously, Symonds somehow missed that the Royal Navyâ€™s own <em>Nelson</em> class battleships mounted larger guns than <em>Hood</em>â€”both <em>Nelson</em> and <em>Rodney</em> were armed with nine 16-inch naval rifles, which were, again, both longer and larger than those on Hood.</p>

